title: Great Looking Kitchen
text: I bought this kitchen for my 2.5 year old twins. I must say that it looks great. It took 2 people about 2 hours to put this together as there are lots of small parts. But I think any kitchen that has reasonable amount of imaginative pieces will have the same problem. The cabinets are amazingly sturdy. The hinges are similar to what you would find in real kitchen cabinets. My twins are constantly slamming doors and having rough play but the kitchen is still withstanding all that. It is not too large to overwhelm my living room but large enough for 2-4 kids to play together. Looks beautiful. I bough Melissa and Dough Pots and Pans, Fridge food, Pantry food, Condiment set, Cake, Cupcakes and Vegetable crate for pretend play. There is still plenty of room. We bought some plastic fruits and teapot set to keep in the top. Great value for money. The only con is that I wish they had managed to add a combo washer and dryer. Some larger kitchens have it but I did not want to get anything that large for just a washer.

title: Blow my brains out
text: Yes it is small. Yes it is nice enough. BUT... 3 hours to assemble. Some screws are painted, some are not, but they are not differentiated in the directions. Not all holes line up, and some parts jut out unnecessarily. Overall a tedious chore to build this thing. Do yourself a favor, get a plastic Fisher Price kitchen and get back 3 hours of your life.

title: Looks nice in our living room and our son plays with ...

title: This kitchen is amazing! It is so cute
text:
This kitchen is amazing! It is so cute! I love the vintage look and that it is wood! My daughter loves it and spends hours playing with it.

Pros:
It is seriously so cute
It is a big heavy piece and stands up pretty well to my daughters rough play
It doesn't have noisy buttons or lights so it is all imagination

Cons:
It took a long time to set up! Lots of steps to build this thing
Since it is painted, as my daughter has played and banged her pots around, it has chipped the color off on parts
The selves and the sink just pop in and out, we are constantly finding them in another room as my toddler wont keep them in

Overall we love this little kitchen. It has provided hours of play time, all imagination based, for my child. We are happy with it and would buy it again!

title: Assembly takes a good while.
text: I purchased this for my playroom because I was going for a modern looking playroom and this fit that look. As far as it being the best kitchen play set out there I wouldn‚Äôt say that. It is pretty basic. The assembly takes a long time and I‚Äôm pretty sure if your not accustomed to assembling things you will hate that you tried this one. You need a electric drill because it would take forever to screw in all those screws by hand. It is also pretty small so it wouldn‚Äôt work for kids bigger than probably 4 years old. I like the white kitchen but that is about all it has going for it. I probably wouldn‚Äôt buy it because it was fun to play with.

title: Five Stars
text: Love it so much!

title: Would not recommend
text:
I got 2/3rds through this and am having issues I can‚Äôt ignore.
The only parts that come preassembled are loosely screwed. I can‚Äôt tighten the screws because the holes are stripped out already, so I had to bust out my wood glue. There are some other divots that came inserted already, that are cracked through the surface of the wood. It‚Äôs frustrating that the only things they did for you are messed up.
I don‚Äôt think there are an excessive number of steps. I‚Äôm not in a rush for a deadline so I can take my time and thoroughly check out the pictures to not miss anything, and you do have to scrutinize EVERY picture, in detail. Other kitchens from KitchenKraft are on the BILT app but not this one. One thing the directions don‚Äôt say but should have, is to check every screw to see if there are options for white or silver heads. I ended up using a lot of the white screws on inner panels without realizing there were options, leaving me with only silver screws on outer panels. The way this is packaged, there‚Äôs no way to know there are variations.
Right now, the side panel of the microwave isn‚Äôt flush with the pack of the unit. However, the groove that the thin back panel slides into is where it‚Äôs supposed to be. It‚Äôs hard to explain, but basically, this is the only way to turn this piece, and it has to be cut wrong. This is on step 23 of 35 that this is coming up, and I can‚Äôt ignore it for the price of the unit. I‚Äôm returning this. Around step 21 or 22, instructions called for me to turn a BLUNT flat screw into a plastic pole with a hole so small, it‚Äôs not possible without a pointy-tipped screw.
It probably took me 3 hours to get 2/3rds through. Most of that was relatively calm and fine, but the above issues slowed me down and ultimately have me trying to unassemble all this work to fit it back in the box. So if you‚Äôre considering spending the time and money on this, consider whether is is worth SIX hours to put together and take apart again so you can get your money back and break even. Sure you might be the lucky one that gets a good one, but is it worth the risk if you are not? My time is worth more than this. I could have spent this time with my son...

UPDATE: my husband convinced me to keep it. We put it together the rest of the way; there was a second piece that sticks out the back also, and it‚Äôs clear neither is supposed to, but there‚Äôs no way to adjust it or install it differently. Maybe it‚Äôs a bad lot. Anyway, our son LOVES this set, so I‚Äôll upping it to 2 stars. It definitely needs to be anchored to the wall as our 18 month old has pulled this over, luckily not onto himself. Our ideal location is in front of a tiled wall, though, so it‚Äôs kind of another strike against this thing to me that it‚Äôs not more bottom-heavy. His favorite part of this is the telephone and the microwave. We may take off the latches for the other cabinets, as it‚Äôs a little difficult for him to open the doors. (We have this on a hardwood floor, so you really need to use one hand to hold the unit in place and the other to open the door, or it slides towards you. A kid his age wouldn‚Äôt have that figured out by now.) our son IS tall for his age, but isn‚Äôt technically ‚Äúold enough‚Äù for this set, and he already towers over it LOL...I would definitely recommend checking the measurements first as this thing is shorter than our fireplace.

text:
Our 2yr old granddaughter loves it, and I like it because it's nice to look at and I can have it in our home without feeling surrounded by cheap plastic stuff in garish colors, or worse yet‚Ä¶.pink. When she's too big for it I'll donate it to a day care center or charity.
Our 2yr old likes all the knobs, doors, shelves‚Ä¶..lots of play value. There's also a good amount of storage for pots, utensils, food, etc. No accessories come with it, so be sure to buy some kitchen stuff and toy food to go with it.
There were other reviewers who said it took them 3hrs or so to put this together. I'm embarrassed to say that it took me A LOT longer than that. She literally played with it uninterrupted for over 2 hours yesterday. Others have said that it is quite small, which I agree, but we have to bend over to access our lower cabinets too, don't we? title: Pain to assemble
text:
The product surely looks cute. My 3 yo loved it. It was cheap (good price). The pros end right here.

Cons - extremely large number of pieces, VERY complicated assembly, MASSIVELY time consuming and confusing and INCORRECT instructions.

Too many unnecessary pieces.

I am not a professional licensed builder or home improvement contractor but I have assembled most of my furniture in the house. It took me about 6 hours. I was very frustrated. As someone else wrote, Ikea assembly looks like a piece of cake. I could assemble an entire BEDROOM set faster than this. And this was after using power tools every step of the way.

Very confusing way of arranging pieces. There are 3 "E" screws and the instructions call for 10 E screws. Wait, there are 7 more E screws all the way at the end. I mean, why couldn't they put all the 10 E screws together and call it a day. Similarly, there are 3 B screws and later on there are 5 more B screws arranged in the package. Just plainly confusing.

Built quality is not the best, sometimes pieces didn't fit together, and had to be forced in. Thanks to my tools, I was able to Ram the pieces in where it was impossible to rectify.

There was no way to determine the orientation of certain key pieces till you had moved 3 steps down in the manual and realize you will have to undo the last 16 minutes to go back and fix it.

Also it's not smooth in the back side. Certain pieces and certain screws stick out of the back, so can't really have the open concept kitchen.

Oh and the final product was wobbly. Had to out a piece of paper under one of the legs after I tried to fix it for 15 minutes.

Frame is medium sturdy. Can't say about durability as it has been less than 6 hours.

title: GOOD TOY, KIDS LOVE IT, HAVE A DRILL AND A FEW HOURS READY
text:
Overall I am pleased with this item, mainly because my Kids are very happy with it! There's quite a bit to mention but I will sum it up as quick and simple while detailed for those who would and should read this.

To get this out of the way, would I buy it again? ABSOLUTELY!, RECOMMEND TO A FRIEND, YES! I would insist that I assemble it though as I'm sure it's easier after the first time!

My Kids are 2 and 3 and they love it very much, I also purchased a kids dish and kitchen utensil kit and very glad I did because it did not come with anything like that however for the price and quality I had no problem spending an extra 20$ for all the items needed to complete it (I'll come back and insert link to set I bought it was great!)

PROS: -Definitely a real wood set very sturdy and doesn't seem cheap at all, 6/5 on quality!
-Comes with all screws needed and every wood piece had small holes drilled so no mishaps going through the wood at an angle! It also came with an "extra" section of screws an extra couple hinges and tid bits!
-Storage space is plentiful, my Kids put all their kitchen play items (and more) in storage spots to where it's not cluttered at all!
-Looks much nicer than a plastic one, all wood was painted splinter free and sturdy!
-Price was very good super quick delivery esp for a fairly heavy item!

CONS AND SIDE NOTES:
-I could put another one of these together in a very short time, but the first time was tedious and time consuming, instructions show all the holes and you have to pay very close attention to the orientation of every one of the many many pieces, maybe not a con but it took me a while.

-IMPORTANT!!! - This comes with a seperate bag that has a flexible but sturdy plastic strap that makes it so you can anchor it into a wall or non movable object, when my 2yr old pulls the kitchen door open I got nervous at how much it moved and I STRONGLY recommend you use the Anchor!

-Alot of pieces, and screws, nuts as well as hinges.. Although high quality again the orientation has got to be dead on or you will be tearing it back apart! Screws are labeled by their letter and then quantity, and not in alphabetical order, also the same "A" screw will have 2 slots one has like 5 white painted head A screws and across the cardboard there are like 10++ "A" screws not painted. (The same letter screw painted or not, are interchangeable.)
-With alot of parts you really need to take inventory first and make sure they are all there. The wood pieces that are #9 (2 of them) will have a _ under the 9 so not to be confused as a #6 even though I don't remember a 6.
-Very tight shutting doors that need to break in a little. Microwave did not and was only door that did not have something to keep it shut so I use small magnet strips to keep it shut!

Ok so it shows in the manual needing a Phillips screwdriver... If you are trying to get away and take your time if you have time then use a screwdriver, I used a light impact electric drill and it saved me hours of time and no damage!
The directions are better than most toys illustrations are visually as helpful as they can be, and the English part is real English not half fast translated, I'm a Man but I read manual many times to be sure.

As simple yet time consuming to assemble honestly I would have paid someone 75$ to assemble it just for the time, but I appreciate it more for my kids because I put it together myself!

Dont Cheat out on screws, they are all there for a good reason and when completed you'll also see why! I did not have to put one single sticker on it that was already good to go which helped ALOT too!

Conclusion: If your a stay at home Mom with no extra time and chasing little ones around all day, I'd recommend having someone (husband boyfriend, girlfriend, just someone else) assemble it and not where the kids can see. Most people should not shy away from this because I say it's tedious to put together. I build electronics and PCS, not much of a carpenter and I use that term because you really do build a real little kitchen! Count every part first and mine came with 1 wooden piece with no number but wasn't hard to figure out, follow instructions to a T don't cut corners, and ANCHOR IT TO SOMETHING STURDY, get frustrated just take a quick break and you'll be fine!
It was a decent amount of more work than I expected but overall I'm confident I made a good choice on this and my kids agree with me!

Hope this helps!

title: Looks super cute, but doesn't hold up well
text:
I bought this kitchen because I wanted something sturdy and life-like, nothing plastic with batteries.

We already have a kidkraft dollhouse, so I figured assembling this wouldn't be much different. Let me tell you - the dollhouse is the novice level and this is the expert level. It comes in a pile of wood and screws. But, the instructions were relatively easy to follow once you have your pieces sorted.

It is all solid wood and very sturdy. I think it will hold up much better than our previous plastic kitchens. The buttons on the microwave and the dials on the oven are painted on - not stickers that can be peeled off. The cabinets are all plenty roomy enough to store play food, but the "water dispenser" is too short for any play cups except teacups. The sink is also just popped into place, so it's definitely possible that a tactical child could remove it.

I had originally looked at a model a bit bigger than this one, but went with this one because the sale price was too good to pass up. You can see my 3 yr old son next to it. He's a hair taller than the fridge, but it's still a good size kitchen for him. However, if your child is already 5+, I would definitely go with a bigger one.

The biggest disappointment was that the microwave door came with a chip in it, but altogether the kitchen looks really nice (seen here with the Melissa and Doug Kitchen Accessory Set) and I'm pretty happy with it. It's not a toy that I mind being out where guests see it. It's been a huge hit with my son, and, since it's for him, he's the final critic here.

ETA: less than one year later, this has not held up well AT ALL. I'll be the first to admit that my kids are hard on toys, but I do also feel that toys should be made to withstand that. The oven door hangs crooked, phone is long since lost, oven shelf is gone, one burner came completely off, the other burner is cracked, wood got dinged. I feel like I should have stuck with a plastic kitchen at this point.

title: Much fun after a lot of work for grandpa
text:
First the good news: The kitchen is the sturdiest toy I've seen in a long time. Made almost entirely of wood, once assembled it will probably stand up to a good workout administered by an energetic toddler. My 2 year old grandson loved it immediately.

Now the not so good news: After seeing an on-line review that said assembly took 2 hours I thought that I knew what to expect. Wrong! It took this 71 year old judge about 5 hours, much of it spent in very twisted positions on the floor, to complete the assembly. Boy was I stiff when I finished! The assembly instructions for this apparently Dutch designed kitchen may very well have been written by an engineer who was high on pot when he visited an Ikea store. Much of the hardware is what you'll find with Ikea furniture, and the instructions are drawings without text. The main problems were that: Some of the drawings involve too many parts at once, so that it can be hard to figure out what goes where; various similar pieces of hardware have almost identical identifications; and the instructions for one of the last steps (attaching the top shelf) refer to incorrect hardware--in two cases a bolt is identified without noting that a particular end fastener must also be used, and in the third case you are told to use a bolt that doesn't fit, and the correct bolt that would screw into the underlying pipe on the end of the shelf is not provided, although the kitchen seems fine without it. Also, earlier on (unless I missed it), you're told neither to affix two door closing fasteners nor which bolts and nuts to do it with.

I'm still happy with the purchase after seeing how much my grandson loves it. I did, however, tell my daughter and son in law "no more project toys."

title: Tough assembly but so cute when complete!
text:
Once you get this put together it is really fun and so cute. The working knobs and faucets are a real hit with my 2 1/2 year old granddaughter. It's the perfect size for her, she loves the cupboards and really enjoys playing with it.

I gave it 4 stars instead of 5 because the assembly was brutal! My husband can take apart engines and transmissions and rebuild them, so he is talented in the area of tedious assembly. This project took almost 5 hours to assemble. The instruction booklet has no words and is a series of pictures with over 30 steps to complete. The other little quirk is you have to pull pretty hard to open the refrigerator and it jerks the whole unit pretty hard. We are going to try and fix that if we can.

I really love the set since all the other kitchens out there are plastic and this is like a finished chip board which is so much nicer. The vintage detailing really makes the unit special, and unique. The assembly, while daunting, can be done if you take your time and complete one step at a time. The end result is a darling kitchen that will last for years.

text: Terrible terrible terrible!!! I will never buy a cheap, China made Kidkraft product again as long as I live and will be sure to spread the word to friends and family as well. Aesthetically, it's the absolute best/nicest looking kitchen I could find that wouldn't be an eye sore in our home (white is such a nice neutral color but it also comes in other colors) and it's significantly smaller than plastic kitchens, without giving up any 'features' (like fake microwave).

I should also mention that at the time I bought this, it was cheaper than listed with sister company, Diapers.com so definitely comparison shop for the best price.

Lastly, we were concerned with how difficult it would be to put together - it was definitely a pain with a million parts but after that's done, it's a pretty sturdy piece.

text:

1. the directions say screw "Q" is supposed to hold the water faucet down, but there are no "Q" screws in the package. Way to waste an hour re-reading and looking through everything trying to find something that isn't there. When I finished putting it all together I see 2 screws labeled "R", low and behold they are the exact size "Q" are supposed to be.
2. The directions have close out shots of some things so you see EXACTLY what you're supposed to do. Not so for the hinges on the doors. It would be nice i that was included. I would have given this a 5 if not for the 2 things I mentioned and there are 2 boards that hang out over the back longer than they're supposed to. Plus one piece of cabinet had a crack in it. text:
The final product is really nice, however putting it together was a bear. I started to put it together and eventually handed over the project to my husband. I'd say total amount of hours was about 4. I agree with many reviewers that the instructions were a joke. What was really annoying is that some screws are painted white and some not, but labelled the same. The white screws are intended for the areas that are exposed on the outside, whereas the silver ones are for the screws only for the inside - the instructions did not indicate which screws to use (white or silver) - so what ended up happening is that some of the silver screws ended up on the outside of the kitchen. I will now have to paint these screws white. Also, despite the fact that the kit included extra screws, we were still missing two screws for the hinges. All in all, we are pretty happy with the product, the assembly was super annoying.

***One more thing I need to add - mine did not come with a microwave turntable as indicated in the product image. I noticed in many reviews that this was missing for other people as well. If you are considering buying this, please be prepared to know that you will most likely not receive the microwave turntable.

title: Great Kitchen Set
text:
This is a fantastic kitchen set we bought for our 22 month old. The quality is what stands out the most - Good solid wood construction with real metal screws and hinges. When assembled, the unit is sturdy and even the plastic handles and sink are well made. While we are very happy with this kitchen, and our daughter absolutely loves it, there are few things you should know ahead of time:

Pros:
* When assembled, the unit is one single piece and very sturdy. It's not top heavy at all and I don't have much concern about it tipping. But if you do, there's an included wall-tie.
* The surfaces are really easy to clean. The first thing my daughter did was walk up to this thing with a purple crayon, but it wiped right off with a wet paper towel.
* The oven door swings out instead of down, which I have read is a safety problem on other kitchens.
* Extra parts! They include a couple extra of each type of screw (there are about 10 different types) and they're in a specific pouch labeled "extra parts". Excellent touch.

Cons:
* There are a lot of pieces. Like about 140 including screws...so be ready to set some time aside for assembly. It took me just over 3 hours to completely assemble this unit. (also, I recommend using your own quality allen wrench - the one that's included doesn't have good bite and there are a few pieces like the feet that are really difficult to get on)
* Because the doors and cabinets are made of real wood, it will sound like real wood smashing together every time your toddler slams the refrigerator door...over and over and over again.
* Each piece is supposed to be labeled with a number, but many of the stickers with the numbers had fallen off. I recommend laying everything out first so you're sure of what's what.

title: Assembly in progress will update when complete
text:
I read quite a few of the reviews both positive and negative before ordering this kitchen, so we went into this expecting an extensive assembly project AND as my review title states my husband is still assembling our kitchen. I decided to start writing my review so that I don't forget the issues that we are having as we go.
Honestly, before we even began assembling we wondered if we had the correct hardware packet included with our kitchen. Seriously, right off the bat things weren't adding up, manual indicates we should have a certain number of a pieces and the packet has a different amount. Then there is R in the hardware kit but no R in the parts list in the manual. Maybe there will be an R further on in the assembly instructions but we would've liked to make sure that we had everything that we needed before we started. Also, assembly instructions indicate that the tools needed are only the ones included, an Allen wrench and another little wrench but a screw driver is clearly needed as well, oh and a drill. One of the pieces of wood is chipped. The piece that will be the counter top, at the edge of the sink. Truly I have already suggested to my husband that we return this kitchen several times but what a hassle? So we've decided to press on. Just now my husband came out to tell me that he was screwing in the last little screw on the back of the refrigerator door, one of four that mounts the "water dispenser" on the fridge door and it broke. Just broke. Mind you, my husband his hand screwing everything, he is not using any drills or electric screw drivers. Which someone else suggested you do because you literally have to screw in every required screw, my husbands hands are already sore.
I also want to make mention that we have assembled an entire household full of IKEA furniture so this is not a matter of inexperience.
I will continue to update this review until assembly is completed. I will also add photos.
I haven't been able to figure out how to label the photos so I'll have to describe what way pic is showing.
Photo #1 is the parts list at the beginning of the assembly manual. Notice parts A 14, A 5, E 14 and E 2, this will be important when I explain photo# 2.
Photo #2 is the hardware. Each grouped by letter and a number indicating how many are included. So referring to photo #1 you will see that the manuals parts list indicates that there will be 19 of part A technically there are but separated in two groups 14 in one and 5 in the other. The group of 5 have white tops the group of 14 has chrome tops. You can NEVER tell when the white topped screws are to be used and when the chrome topped screws are to be used. This is also the case with parts E, there are the correct amount but separated and some have white tops and some have chrome, no indication of when to us which.
Photo #3 shows the broken screw that I mentioned earlier in my review.
Photo #4 shows the chip in the wood on the counter top at the edge of the sink. It arrived that way, we discussed returning it but decided that we could do that and receive another one with other damage, this was fairly minor and maybe the sink will partially conceal it once in place. I'll let you know.
Now it would seem that some of our actual panels have been mislabeled, luckily we caught it before we began screwing them into place. I don't know if the item that we received was a return or just a total factory reject?
7 hours later (including a lunch and restroom break) so it probably took about 5 hours of solid work to assemble.
End result picture #5 our son LOVES it.
However, it is not as high quality as other reviewers claimed. I don't know what they're used to.? The mystery of parts R was never resolved but as you can see from photo # 2 there were quite a few parts labeled "extra" so ...?
I guess that doesn't matter though, in the end our son just loves opening and closing the fridge, oven, and cabinets and stirring his lil pots on the stove. And we enjoy the retro look that fits in with our actual kitchen.
I probably would not recommend this kitchen to anyone if asked.
P.S. Photo #6 the sink in place does conceal the chip. The sink is removable so I will have to glue the chip down so that our son doesn't get scraped or a sliver.

I was wary about assembly, but I assembled it on my own in 2.5 hours while 9 months pregnant. I took my sweet time, and as long as you do it patiently, follow diagrams very carefully, and only take screws/hardware out as needed, you should be fine. Considering its complexity, the directions are possibly better than IKEA directions. An automatic drill with screwdriver attachment really sped things up. I used a couple little bowls for holding loose hardware, and foam mats to protect hardwood floors during assembly. Don't try to assemble this with kids running around, it would be infinitely harder!

title: A strong and sturdy kitchen that is fun for the whole family!
text:
We love the style of this kitchen. Since it is white it blends in with our décor. It is an impressive looking kitchen that would compliment any home décor. I especially like that it is vintage without being dated. Kudos to KidKraft on a fabulous design.

This play kitchen is small but mighty! It is easy to move around and small enough that when it is not in use it can be easily stored. We love how compact this play kitchen is making it easy to move around the house {we change where our play areas are frequently to keep things fresh}.

We are a huge fan of functionality of this kitchen. Every door has a handle and is able to open and close. Every knob turns. Each door is also furnished with a cabinet latch that prevents the cabinets from swinging open on their own.

My children love that their kitchen mimics mommy's kitchen. The stove and microwave can both be seen through and the microwave has a turntable! These features make pretend play in the play kitchen that much more realistic for them.

Another great and well thought out feature is the removable sink. My boys have a tendency to get sticky little fingers on everything. They also like to play with their real snacks in their play kitchen. Being able to easily remove the sink to clean is extremely convenient.

The White Vintage Kitchen does not come fully assembled. It does come with detailed step-by-step pictorial instructions. Although it took us about two hours to put together, we had a fun time working on this project as a family. My three-year-old son especially loved being daddy's little helper.

I am a huge fan of the White Vintage Kitchen. KidKraft did an amazing job creating a stylish and sturdy play kitchen. I am fully confident in the quality of this KidKraft product and believe that it will stand the test of time with my children. This is a strong sturdy piece of play equipment that my children love. I adore that it is clean, simple, and tasteful. (I was given a KidKraft White Vintage Kitchen for the purposes of a blog review. To read more about my review of this product and see a video review and pictures of this product in use please visit "Mom Mart")

title: Good product, but a pain to assemble
text:
CONS
- LOOOONG ASSEMBLY - ll the reviews saying it's hard to assemble are correct. There are like 50+ parts and it took me at least 6 hours. Much of that time is the result of me unscrewing and re-screwing the plain screws or the painted screws or vice-versa. That is, there are identical painted screw that show on the exterior, and plain screws on the interior, but they're labeled exactly the same in the instructions which never differentiate. You do figure that out eventually though.

- WALL ANCHOR COMPLETELY USELY - There is no possible way to screw it in unless you want it to show at the top or have a screw driver that is less than 5 inches long if you want to hide it behind the kitchen itself.

- KIND OF SHORT - One thing I'm concerned about actually is it's height. My kids are both 15 months old, and when they really understand what this is for, it seems they will tower over it

PROS

FEELS PRETTY STURDY and does look like a pretty quality product. My screw driver might slip sometime on the surface, but never left a scratch, so I have some confidence it can take a beating.

GOOD LOOKIN'

KIDS VERY DRAWN TO IT - Our kids are pretty young to understand exactly what this is, but they're pretty drawn to it. They really like opening and closing the doors, putting stuff in, etc. Lots of moving parts and the like.

title: Takes a long time to assemble, finished product pays off
text:
We ordered this for our 2yr old as her big Santa gift, after comparing many many kitchens- I was having a hard time deciding...A friend saw it on sale for $99 on cyber Monday and I didn't hesitate at that price- definitely shop around before purchasing as many sites carry this exact kitchen at a wide range of prices. I am glad I went for it as we are pleased with it overall. Thankfully, my husband started assembling a couple nights before Christmas- it took about 4+ hours total of assembly time for my husband by himself, the time was broken up and he wasn't in a hurry- so *maybe* it can be done in less. We know others who own it who gave a similar time frame though- at least 3 hrs. My husband did say that it was not difficult, just tedious & time consuming. He didn't have trouble with the instructions but he was pretty frustrated by all the little parts & steps during the process- despite all this, even he seemed won over once our daughter saw it.

Cons- long assembly time- lots of parts, there were marks/scratches on several of the pieces that seemed to have occurred during packaging- none of them affected the function or were damaging to the structure & fortunately none of them were on the visible exterior- I feel this was just luck though so I'd recommend looking at it as soon as it arrives to make sure all pieces are in good shape in case you need to send back etc, the stove knobs should make a clicking sound- 2 of the them broke/stopped clicking almost immediately- the inside part that makes them click is plastic & not very substantial (my daughter will never know the difference & it doesn't matter to me, but it bothered my husband that they don't function as intended)

Pros- Most importantly- my child loves it...it's absolutely adorable & looks exactly as pictured- very aesthetic & appealing- if you like the Pottery Barn kitchens but not the price tag - this is a budget friendly & comparable option, I liked that it's available in white (which we chose)- more realistic than others on the market and also gender neutral, hinges are sturdy- as are the doors/other parts, all edges are smooth & rounded- no sharp pieces or corners to bump into as i saw in negative reviews of similar products, the entire kitchen is good quality/feels stable but the whole thing is also easy for adults to move around while still not easy for a toddler to tip over (it does come with what you need to attach it to wall for added safety if needed), it offers all parts of the kitchen in one compact piece- it doesn't take up a huge amount of space but stills gives the feel of a full sized play kitchen- and includes the refrigerator (& a microwave which doesn't really fit the vintage theme but its a part of our busy life here in 2013 & my daughter went for it first out of every other feature!) unlike others in this size & price range, I also like that the sink comes out- I'm not sure how much you'd want water in it- but you *could* take it out to wash it or to empty water out if it ended up in there...once it was assembled, I felt the door latches were a little tight & worried my daughter might have a little trouble opening/closing the doors but she had no trouble at all. The stove door has the handle at the top (like a real stove) but the stove door actually opens on the side- this was confusing for my daughter at first but she quickly figured it out. I can understand why they did it this way- it would probably end up being stood on & eventually broken if they'd made it the way it seems like it should go. I was torn about ordering this versus one with more "bells & whistles" (such as the step2 kitchens) ultimately though, I think the simplicity of this fosters more creative play as it doesn't do all the work for her! Her imagination is still hard at work without it needing to make sounds, lighting up & so forth...plus, no batteries and less things to stop working! Another small added bonus is, everything is painted on this kitchen versus stickers -which often get peeled off, faded & damaged with time.

(Side note- Most of the toy food & kitchen toys- variety of brands- we had already are to scale with this kitchen, including the IKEA brand toy pots & pans, however the IKEA baking set comes with cookie pans & those do not fit flat in this oven)

The small size of this could be a pro or con- my daughter is a petite 2yr old and it is perfect for her...however, I almost wish we had ordered it awhile back to increase length of play time. She can reach everything perfectly now & loves it, but will probably be taller than the kitchen by age 3- i think she will still play with it even after that but given her current height, she could have probably handled something taller/larger already, so if your child is older or taller at the time of ordering, id recommend just ordering something taller to begin with & alleviating any concern that your child will quickly outgrow it. I did look at the measurements before ordering & measured the space we planned to put it in and knew it was on the smaller side, seeing it in person though -it still just seems a little smaller than expected. I just recommend really comparing the size of this to your child's height before ordering- if my child was older, I think I would have been disappointed in this size. I see people who've mentioned this for older children (over 3-4) and I really couldn't imagine ordering this for a preschooler versus a toddler. Again though, the sizing can be a positive or negative feature, depending on your particular child/house- if you're like us, we have so many other toys so it's actually nice to get the kitchen experience without it taking up an entire play room.

I would recommend this kitchen to others, particular those ordering for children under 3. I'd also order KidKraft again based on this product- even though it was a pain to assemble.

title: Disappointed in product and customer service
text:
We bought this kitchen for our one-year-old daughter who loves playing with the play kitchen at her grandparents house. Her grandparents actually picked this one out and had it shipped to us, so I didn‚Äôt get a chance to read the reviews or really research the kitchen much prior.

My first disappointment came with the fact that the microwave is missing the turntable that is both listed in the description and shown in the company stock photos provided for the product. While this might not seem like a big deal to most, one of the things we were excited about with this kitchen was the turntable because we thought it would resemble a Lazy Susan which we have in our kitchen, and my daughter loves to play with. I‚Äôve been in touch with customer service who is unwilling to send the item to me to complete our kitchen. It seems as though they are aware of the mistake on the Amazon listing, and have been for weeks according to other commenters, and have yet to fix the information. This is horrible marketing and customer service.

My next issue is with the size of this kitchen. Right now, at 12 months, the kitchen is actually the perfect size for my daughter. She can reach everything, including the top shelf of the refrigerator and the microwave. However, it does not fit the Melissa and Doug cookie sheets or any bulky kitchen sets, and I fear that by next year she will be too big for it. It has no place to hang utensils or cups, so I had to add command hooks to the side to try and add extra storage. While this kitchen seems sturdy and well-built, it definitely will not grow with your child.

I was going to give this product one star because of the horrible customer service, the small size, and the fact that it took me over five hours to put together even though I am quite savvy with this sort of thing. Even though it was very easy to follow the instructions, the assembly was so time-consuming. The company should really add the door hinges before shipping, that would‚Äôve saved a lot of time. I added an extra star because my one year-old can reach all the components of this kitchen, and seems to enjoy it.

title: Long time to assemble but worth it!
text: This kitchen is adorable.  The kids LOVE it.  I thought it would be too tiny, but it is perfect for a 2 year old ‚Äî and her 5 year old brother is having a great time too.  Yes, there are a lot of pieces, 40 to be exact.  And about 150 screws!  There are also 35 steps to do as you assemble this kitchen, with picture diagrams only ‚Äî no words!  It will take you a few hours ‚Äî not one or two ‚Äî more like 4 to 6 ‚Äî or more!  It is a long process.  Our pieces were in perfect condition,  well-labeled, and everything went smoothly.  Grandpa, a farmer who knows how to build and fix most everything, took most of the day to assemble this set (a break for lunch and supper).  It is well-made and super cute.  We would buy it again.  He did need to use a drill to make one set of screw holes bigger, with no success, so opted to replace that set with smaller screws from his own toolbox.  This set is probably not for the novice.....  another set of hands might be helpful.

title: Fun, but annoying assembly and misfit parts.
text:
I'm on the fence about this kitchen; it's a great little setup once it's assembled, and my toddler loves it, but boy was it a pain to put together! I'm honestly not sure it's worth the trouble compared to other options out there (Ikea etc).

It took 4 hours, no joke, to put it together, and I'm quite handy with these kinds of things. On top of that, 2 parts didn't fit quite right, so I had to work around them to get the thing up and running enough for my kid to play with. I've emailed kidkraft to request replacements, but it's very frustrating when you're 3 hours in to realize that it won't be perfect once you're finally done.

I picked this kitchen since my kid loved playing with it at an AirBnB we stayed at, especially the phone which other models don't have. It also has a refrigerator, which I thought would be fun, but it mainly serves as storage, so if I had to choose all over again I'd probably pick another model and just get a small toy phone to go with it.

Honestly if I hadn't run into the two misfit pieces I'd probably give it four stars. Five for fun, minus one for assembly. If kidkraft sends me new pieces and they fit, I'll update my review accordingly.

title: Assembling this is a nightmare

It took my husband 4 hours to put this together.  My husband happens to be a very patient man with an ability to put just about anything together, but this almost changed him for good. He experienced anger and emotional and physical pain while trying to put this together. It wasn't till he tightened the last screw and saw how our son immediately fell in love with it did he mention how this toy may have been worth the living hell he experienced putting it together. All that aside it is a quality toy with attention paid to every last detail. If you think you can take this project on then by all means put it in your basket and purchase it.

title: cute but be prepared for CONSTRUCTION
text:
This is a cute kitchen, perfect for my average-sized 21 month old. She loves it! I will say that it is fairly small and compact, which is what I wanted for now since I have a small kitchen. It is the perfect size for her now - microwave is at perfect standing height - but I can't imagine a 3 year old or bigger playing with it - it would just to be small and short. Also, I can't imagine more than 1 child, especially older toddlers, playing together; it's really built for one. But, for the purpose of a young toddler, it is great. I would give it a 5 based on final appearances and the fact that my daughter loves it and I think it is sturdy and of good quality. But....

Be prepared for some work to get it together! The reviews seem to indicate an average of 2-3 hours to build it. I think either those reviewers had someone else helping them, are very very good at mechanical things, or underestimated the time. I think I'm a smart woman and not inexperienced at putting together my share of Ikea furniture, but this almost brought me to my knees. I estimate 6-8 hours total. I highly recommend a previous suggestion to separate all hardware and place into individually labelled plastic baggies - the way they are packaged is very weird. I was fortunate to have every piece and so had no issues with that, unlike some other reviewers. My biggest issue was with the sheer physicality of the assembly. The pieces are small, and you have to turn a million little screws into little bolts, etc with this small Allen wrench and little awkward wrench......my hands and fingertips are still sore 48 hours later. I really think that some of this assembly could have been predone. For example, 4 of 5 doors came with hinges prescrewed on - one did not, and it was a painful exercise in manual dexterity to get the hinge on the door. Why couldn't that have been done? Also, while generally everything "worked" and I did not find the pictoral instructions difficult, some the of bolt parts were not of good quality. For example, in 2 places I had A screws that would not completely screw into B locking bolts. Turns out that if not angled correctly, B bolts warp and become nonfunctional. Must be the reason why 2 extra A screws and B bolts are provided (there is no other extra hardware provided). Problem is that B bolts are now stuck in the wood and I can't get them out, which means that those corners are not secure. Overall, it doesn't matter, the unit is stable, but it was a time sink trying to get that to work and it still isn't right. PITA! Make better hardware already!

title: Like others have said
text:
Like others have said, this thing is not easy to put together. I'm an IKEA veteran. I have a freaking black belt in allen wrenches. It still took me 3 hours (till 2 am on Christmas Eve eve, but that's freaking parenthood amiright) even with my husband trying to help. You have to pay really close attention to how pieces are oriented in the photo instructions, and there are just a TON of pieces. Pay attention to which pieces face the outside of the toy, and use the white screws where they're going to show and the silver screws where they won't... I didn't do well with this, but luckily had some white craft paint to fix that mistake.

That being said, we got it together with only one time-wasting error and it is very, very solid. We have a very active toddler who really loves to slam doors, and I don't think even he could break it. I predict that it'll last for years, and then probably live on at a local preschool once we've finished loving it.

The playset is super cute. I love that it doesn't make my family room look like a daycare the way a lot of plastic toys do. Buying it in white may have been a mistake, but it was the least expensive option and the construction is so high quality that I'd be willing to put in the energy to repaint it if it got grungy a few years down the line.

There are literally 30+ pieces of covered "wood" and a million screws / small parts. Yikes! Not one thing comes pre-assembled.

text: We ordered this for our granddaughter for Christmas. Let me just say that if you embark on this adventure you are going to owe your husband a burger and a couple of beers for putting this bad boy together. First off, it was disappointing to open the box to broken pieces. I have reached out to customer service with no response, automated call...heavy call volume...blah, blah, blah. Amazon offers full return and replace or refund only. With just a few days before Christmas the chances of getting a replacement are likely slim so I am going to take the little broken bowl and drive all over town trying to find one in the same circumference over the next 72 hours; pretty excited about that. My husband and I both are fairly handy people but wow, these instructions make Ikea instructions look like a work by Shakespeare and somehow they get worse as you get closer to the end of the little booklet. I think the author gave up on life as this document developed; or rather failed to develop. Hardware has an alpha labeling system but there are multiple components labeled with the same letter. Our box had two segments labeled G but they were different size screws and a different count. Some screws in the same segment had the heads painted white while others do not. If you can get through the assembly and remain semi-sane it is a sturdy little kitchen for a toddler and cute, or would be if it had arrived intact.

text: Unlike some other reviewers I had little trouble putting this together quickly by myself (disclaimer my entire house was IKEA for over a decade so I‚Äôm not an amateur at self assembly and have developed nerves of steel, as well as the ability to swear in Swedish at moments of frustration). title: Cute but could be much better
text: I bought this for my grand-daughter. A warning to anyone giving this as a Christmas present - don't wait until Christmas eve and think you are going to whip it together. Assembly takes quite a while. Lots of hardware and some pretty silly placement. You'll need a stubby Phillips screwdriver to get to some of the screws. The hinges are a pain. There are 8 hinges and each requires 4 screws and nuts. The nuts strip very easy - make sure you start them by hand and get them on straight.  There were only two spare nuts provided  - I stripped 3. Also two of the screws (A & G) have both painted and unpainted versions in the kit. The instructions don't say anything about that - they let you figure it out yourself.  At that point you either disassemble and swap the unpainted screws to inside locations or live with it. Unfortunately I'm not the live with it type so even more assembly time moving screws around. Why Kidcraft didn't label the painted screws a different letter I don't understand. I guess they didn't realize there's 26 letters in the alphabet.  They could make this product much better and cut assembly time way down by having thread formed holes on the hinges instead of the 36 low quality tiny nuts. Also 2 parts seem to be too long - Item 5 (top of fridge) and Item 38 (right side of microwave) but fortunately it's at the back of the kitchen. It does expose some bare non-laminated wood but it's not too noticeable. Also seems weird they didn't put a latch on the microwave door - all the other doors have them.  Overall it's not bad quality and is very cute.

title: A nightmare
text: At first I was just overwhelmed with the insane amount of parts to this thing. But I thought ‚ÄúI wanted this vintage-looking kitchen for my kid, so I can do this.‚Äù But my frustration quickly grew. It started with unclear instructions. For example, it labels all screws by letters, but then those lettered screws come in 2 categories: ones with white heads and ones with the plain metal heads. It doesn‚Äôt specify which ones to use where so I had to teach myself that the white ones would be visible from the outside of the unit as to ‚Äòblend in.‚Äô That‚Äôs great- but tell me that in the instructions folks. To top it off, there were never enough white-head ones to amount to what is visible from the outside of the unit. When I got more of the unit put together, I noticed some pieces were obviously. It wrong, because they stick out of the back of the unit in an inconsistent way (see pictures). Now, I am a smart human being, and I‚Äôve put together a lot of furniture. When screws and parts were a pain or didn‚Äôt seem to fit together in a cohesive way, I triple checked the numbers on the boards and the letters on the screws to make sure I was doing it correctly. What I got wrong I corrected, but much I got right, and it looks like crap. What started out as an exciting project turned into a hunk of junk in my daughters‚Äô playroom. Not worth the money.

title: Awesome 1st play ktichen
text:
This is a fabulous little kitchen for our 19month old. I wanted something on the small side, without crazy kid colors as it will be in our main living space. This definitely fits the bill. My only two complaints that keep it from getting 5 stars is 1) the sink bowl is very easy for little people to remove. Our daughter seems to like to remove it all the time. and 2) The shelf in the refrigerator is also removable. For our daughter who is small it is over her head and she has pulled it out and had it fall on her. Both of these are easy fixes though. We are going to glue the sink in place and screw the shelf into place.

FYI our daughter also managed to pull the entire kitchen down on herself (trying to climb it) before we had a chance to attach it to the wall, so make sure you use the provided wall strap.

title: but the joy on a little girls face on Christmas morning made ...

title: Read instructions fully before assembly!
text:
Took around four hours to assemble but well worth it. Is it perfect? No. Is it perfect for us? Yes.

The initial boxing took longer than expected. This is because the protective foam was essentially snow foam by the time the package made it to my house. Lots of vacuuming before I could start assembling.

Now, here are some tips for assembly:

Some parts are labeled with the same letter. The difference, I noticed, was some were painted white and some weren‚Äôt. So keep in mind where you‚Äôd want the painted screw heads to be (facing outside).

Look ahead. I repeat. Look at the instructions ahead. Read the whole thing before starting because I noticed some of the illustrations were inaccurate and I had to redo a couple of steps.

KidKraft doesn‚Äôt recommend using power tools, so get those arms working. I can see why they didn‚Äôt, though. In one of the boards, there is a plastic piece that locks the screws. Well, I‚Äôm no Super Woman, but apparently even with my own strength I was able to almost pry the plastic piece out.

Once finished, this is one glorious play kitchen. Sturdy, beautifully made, and cute design. My daughter especially loved that the stove knobs ‚Äúclicks‚Äù for a real feel. The clamps for the cabinet doors are tight now but I can see it loosening over time. The painted buttons on the microwave will most likely fade too.

Gorgeous kitchen! I probably love it more because I spent 4 hours building this bad boy and I don‚Äôt ever want to give it away.

It is compact, but my twins are now 6 and my daughter 4, and they still play with it almost every day. This kitchen is sturdy enough to hand down to grand kids, and attractive enough to leave out in the open. (I am typing this in our combined study/play room with it right next to me.) My one complaint is that the faucet is plastic and the sink bowl is too easy to remove. The first thing my daughter did was grab the plastic faucet and it made a creaking sound that made me nervous. title: Adorable, functional
text:
Our 14 month old loves visiting the local library and playing in their kids' kitchen. We wanted something for our living room, so we were in the market for something that we wouldn't hate looking at every day. This perfectly fits the bill. It's adorable, sturdy, functional, and he loves it.

I did the assembly myself in about 3 hours, and I am not even remotely handy. I had read that some buyers had an issue with a missing Q or R screw, but that seems to be resolved, as I had no issue finding the pieces and hardware I needed. I found the instructions fairly easy to follow and all of the pieces appropriately labeled, but I did often take a minute to study the assembly picture to ensure that I was orienting the pieces and parts correctly, dreading the possibility of disassembly if I had to resolve something I'd done wrong. If you are patient and meticulous with assembly, it's time consuming but not difficult. Overall, we are really happy with this purchase.

title: I am happy with the outcome
text: I had such high hopes for the assembly when I opened the package. The box was well organized, the wooden pieces were labeled with numbered stickers, the screws were organized in a box with perforations and labeled well. This is not a job for one person and is not something that should be assembled on Christmas Eve. With two people working diligently it took about 2 1/2 hours to get to the last part: the oven door. That's when things went south. The holes on the hinges didn't match up with the holes on the door and when we finagled it so it would the door hit the other door when it shut, leaving it ajar. My husband had to drill more holes in the hinges, making them wider so we cohld adjust the door to the right height and have it close properly. Over all the assembly took about 5 hours, with power drills. I am happy with the outcome. I think it looks adorable and that my daughter will love it, but I would not buy it again until the holes are properly placed.

title: Great toy for so many ages
text:
We received the white vintage Kidkraft kitchen as a gift for my daughter's first birthday. I loved the packaging that KidKraft sent. All of the nuts, bolts and screws, along with every tool except a screw driver, were included. Each piece was labeled and easy to access. They weren't just thrown into a baggy, for you to figure out what goes where. This made putting together the kitchen much easier. It took me about 3 hours total to put it together but that's only because it is a great quality product with all the necessary items to keep it in good shape for years and years of use and abuse by children!

All of the large pieces were labeled with numbers. The screws and bolts were labeled with letters. The instructions were clear and easy to read drawings. It reminded me of Ikea instructions and I find these work out great for products like this one.

Once the kitchen was put together, I found it to be extremely good quality and sturdy. My daughter is only 1 year old now but I see her using this for years and years to come. We put it up in our kitchen so she can cook while we cook. Even as a 1 year old, she enjoys opening the doors, putting things into the cabinets, pulling things out and shutting the doors. KidKraft really won us over with this product!

text: A lot of mixed reviews on here about this item. It does take a little time to put together. You just have to have a little patience. title: Great kitchen for small spaces
text:
Great kitchen for small spaces. We have a small space and this fit perfectly and is cute - it looks nice, not like some cheap kitchen that has features you can't really make out. Love the vintage look. The oven and storage cabinet can't be closed at the same time - for some reason they just don't fit together. They both close next to each other and won't close at the same time. I also wish there was a shelf in the freezer to allow for better organization of the items in there, and maybe even another shelf in the fridge too. I don't think we have a TON of food and it's hard to fit it all in. It would be cool if the microwave buttons or oven buttons beeped when you pushed them - my daughter does just fine making the sound effects herself, and I know it would require replacing batteries and all, but it would just be cool. You can turn the microwave turntable which is cool.

Installation took forever - probably 3-4 hours, with 2 adults working on it. This was started late Xmas eve, and we were up WAY later than expected putting this thing together. So plan for that.

All in all, great purchase and just what we needed - a cute kitchen that is not overbearing or large or ugly. Simple and cute.

title: Nice kitchen...KidKraft could incorporate some electronics...
text:
First off my 16 month old has really enjoyed her kitchen. It is essentially all wood so it is extremely sturdy and I am quite confident it will last. The assembly wasn't too bad. I would say it took about 2.5 to 3 hours although I wasn't in a huge rush.
The white makes it look very clean...that will be hard to beat by other kitchens which my wife loves. :)
When my daughter went over my parents to play with the standard grandchild kitchen that has made it through a previous granddaughter we noticed a cool feature this model was lacking...electronics. My daughter is constantly trying to play with the remote, Ipads, kitchen radio, microwave, dehumidifier, or anything else that beeps or makes a noise or light flash when you push it.
So overall...I would give the looks, craftsmanship, sturdiness 5 stars. Just better features on other units.

title: Be prepared to become Bob the Builder...
text:
Luckily I saw the video posted with this product before ordering. I think if I had not, I would've rated this product lower. Sad, but true. It still shocked me how many pieces arrived.
This product came in a relatively small box for what it was, was a great price, but definitely had NOTHING put together for me. I had to put in every. single. screw. Except in one small area on the microwave door hinge area.
That said, I had fair warning that I would be putting everything together, paid a low price, and the pieces fit together well. I had only two real complaints about this product:
1. The directions never state to screw in the top "counter" (the part holding the sink and burners) to the rest of the kitchen. If you don't notice this, you will have a counter that will lift easily on the left side. I used the "extra" screws included for this, and at the end noted that there were enough in the regular "screw A" area to cover this. It just wasn't listed on the directions anywhere--and I hunted for it. Hopefully newer editions of the instructions will catch this.
2. Plastic pieces - the plastic pieces seem cheaper than usual, although the wood seems fairly good. The silvery "paint" already chipped in a few places while I was putting it together, and my child hasn't even seen this present yet. But my MAIN complaint about the plastic? It is so incredibly difficult to screw anything into it!! I hated the pole at the side and the burners -- I was afraid to use any power tools for fear it would break the plastic, and I was putting all my weight into screwing it together in a more controlled manner. Grabbed my spouse when my hands started hurting and even then one screw wouldn't go all the way down. I would say the plastic is not "predrilled" and this is a huge problem.

Even with the few flaws, this kitchen did go together well with very few predrill holes issues in the wood itself. It is very cute when put together, and I know my chef-inspired son will love it when he gets it for his birthday. I was increasingly pleased with the little kitchen the further I got while building it. For a moderately novice builder, I was pleased with the outcome and felt each step (excluding the missing one) was not too hard to do by myself, although it took a few days of consistent work. It does, however, require a good amount of pressure to screw in any plastic pieces, and the pole and burners required a lot more pain than was necessary.

title: It took me 6 hours but it was a fantastically fun project even on Christmas Eve
text:
I just put this together for my grand daughter. It took me 6 hours but it was a fantastically fun project even on Christmas Eve! It is adorable kitchen! Wow. It is made of wood with all the details you hope for! A winning little kitchen!!! I want to mention that if you like putting things together you'll LOVE doing this. My husband and others absolutely did NOT want to sign on for this project but for me it was an incredibly fun well-done puzzle. All the pieces and instructions are perfect - with one major exception. NOTE! For me the feet of this kitchen didn't have screws that could match. Please check to see that the screws that are in your kitchen match the feet. We ended up buying pointed tip screws and glue but the issue was the hard time we had getting the feet off that were half-on. That's why I'm
writing this review to alert you of that. Overall it's a GREAT little kitchen! GREAT instructions! GREAT project for the person who enjoys putting puzzles together for a few hours.
(I personally had the best time doing this for my grand daughter yet am happy to tell my son in law that he doesn't have to do it. The other option is to get a handyman. : )

title: My daughter loves her kitchen
text:
We bought this for our daughter for her second birthday, and it has been a huge hit! Yes, it took a few hours to put together, but it came with all the parts and the directions were basically easy to follow. I like that it comes with all major appliances (fridge, freezer, oven, stove, and sink), and there is plenty of storage space for dishes and pots/pans. I also like that it is white and does not take up a huge foot print in our room. Our daughter enjoys opening and closing the various compartments, and I know she'll enjoy more make-believe play with it as she gets older.

We purchased the kitchen along with the following items:

[[ASIN:B000BSZ04W Learning Resources - Breakfast, Lunch and Dinner Foods, Set of 44]]--I like the baskets the food comes in (stores nicely on top of the kitchen), but I am not as impressed with the diversity/quality of the actual food.

title: Great Kitchen!
text:
Let me just start by saying this kitchen is great and I highly recommend it. If you are comparing it to others one thing you will notice is that it is shorter than most of the others. This ended up being exactly what we needed. My daughter is almost two and it is the perfect height. Her cousins have a different kidkraft model and it is too tall! She can't even reach the microwave. So even though this one is shorter, don't let that turn you off to it.

I put this together one evening by myself and it took about 2-3 hours while watching football. Maybe would have been less had it been a boring game. It is definitely high quality and was not difficult to put together, just time consuming. My daughter plays with it daily and really really loves it. The only complaints I think I would have is that at the beginning my daughter had trouble opening some of the doors. She has gotten better at it so its not a big problem anymore. The other thing is that you need to supervise while the kids are playing because the corners of some of the doors are sharp. My daughter likes to leave the doors open while playing and she has bumped her head a few times.

Like I said at the beginning though, definitely buy it if you are looking for a kitchen. It is well made, easy to put together, and my daughter just loves it!

title: Very retro and adorable, Looks just like pictured
text:
Very retro and adorable, Looks just like pictured, however I would not buy again and wish I could return, but I already put it together as a Christmas present for my daughter and the boxes were discarded.
Cons:
1.it is very very small and Very short so much that my newly 2 year old will probably outgrow it by march 2017. Compartments are very small. Microwave doesn't stay closed.
2. I love putting together these types of projects, but the screws and amount of hardware was truly excessive. Some of the exact same screws also had some metal tops and some white tops (for the visible outside touches), however there are no instructions saying when to use which, so we ended up with some white and some metal showIng. Instructions could be much better. It also took about 3 hours to do with another person, so prepare to get frustrated.
3. I have a niece that wanted a kitchen too, but she didn't tell me that until after I ordered this one for my daughter, so I bought her an IKEA kitchen since i have an IKEA relatively close to me. The IKEA kitchen was much better. Bigger, tall, more roomy compartments, and the assembly was straightforward( and that's says A LOT, especially for IKEA which is notorious for difficulty)

All in all, I am dissatisfied with my purchase. Wish I had never wasted my money.

title: Great product, but depends on your child's personality
text:
This is a beautiful high quality product. I got my daughter the one in white so as to match our own kitchen cabinets. She received it for Christmas when she was about 1.5 years old. She has had it for several months now.

First, building it was a little bit difficult. My brother who does manual labor with tools all day found it to be a bit tedious and difficult to tighten things in (like the legs) without hurting his hands from the turning of the screws. Some of the wood split from the pressure of the screws going in. But he built it by himself in approximately two hours, while snacking on Christmas cookies.

I bought a bunch of food and pots and pans to go with it, and as nother Christmas gift my daughter got a table and chair set. For Christmas morning we filled it up with the food, and the table set for a meal. Since she is too young to unwrap everything I just put big bows on it. When my daughter came down in the morning and saw it all she was amazed.

She played with the set for a great deal the first few days, but her interest waned after awhile. Over the past few months, the table and chairs seemed to have been a better gift for her age because she liked to sit at a table for her size and play with crayons or playdoh. Despite the kitchen not being one of her favorite toys, I couldn't imagine not having it. It is a nice looking piece, and has plenty of storage for fake food and other toys.

I think as she gets older she will appreciate it more. I wanted to get this brand because the children's museum near us has one in red and my daughter liked playing with it whenever we went there. I suspect, that at this young age, she might have been more engaged by a kitchen set that was more colorful, and made noises and effects. But, I think I would find a garish color or loud noises to be tiring after awhile.

I think it was worth the investment as a standard toy for a child's collection, much like a doll house, or a swing set would be. It is a good storage unit as well. I know we have many years of use ahead of us, since she is almost 2 now. It might be that playing kitchen is not very engaging for her yet.

title: Horrible Assembly, but Your Best Option Out There
text: Adorable - best looking kitchen I could find. I wanted a normal color that preferably matched our own white kitchen cabinets and one that wouldn‚Äôt be an eyesore in our home for a few years. I love the cabinet function (solid doors that open, & no battery powered features to break!), but do really wish the sink knobs turned (my son is trying really hard to turn them) and that all cabinets had a latch. Some catch a latch, others just lightly ‚Äúset‚Äù on the frame when closed. Although one tiny screw from a latch on the fridge section did actually fall out almost immediately. The screws are extremely cheap quality and we had to rig one with a spacer because it wouldn‚Äôt go through the thin particle board as designed üôÑ... As other reviewers state, this takes HOURS to assemble, even when you‚Äôre capable and handy. Just a ton of pieces, so don‚Äôt count on a quick turnaround time if this is a gift. Comes with a TON of extra hardware, which is always unnerving, but we had to use a number of ‚Äúextra screws‚Äù when some of the intended screws were the wrong size for their intended jobs. The issue here is the extra screws don‚Äôt have white-painted caps to match the kitchen. Easily fixed with white craft paint of course. My biggest issue is that the counter is only attached with loose pegs so we will reinforce that ourselves soon as my son has managed to un-peg it a few times, creating a temporary gap with the lower cabinets. However, despite the horrible assembly process (why I deducted a star) I think it‚Äôs one of the better ones out there - I didn‚Äôt want plastic that might crack and of the plywood kits this had the most promising reviews. Glad I got it- but glad I‚Äôll never have to assemble a play kitchen again. Good gift for a nearly-2-year old child.

text: The packaging on this was great and it was really compact for what it turns out to be, so don't worry if you got the right thing. After about 2 hours of me and my wife putting this together it was finally complete. This does take a while to put together and there are some pieces that are very similar so be careful when you put it together or you will spend a lot of that time taking things apart. When it is put together though, it is a great little kitchen! The doors open and shut very well and the locking mechanisms work well and continue working after a lot off use. The only disclaimer I would write about is the microwave door. It doesn't have a locking mechanism like the other doors, but there is an extra one included if you're not scared of drilling a couple holes. What I did was stuck a velcro strip on the door and it works perfectly. The faucet and nobs swivel. The oven nobs have  a cool clicking mechanism that I thought was a sweet addition. Also you might want to strap this to the wall with the included straps if you have smaller kids. All in all this is a great kid kitchen and well worth the price.

title: GREAT PRODUCT! Even I want to play with it but the instructions are pretty crappy!
text:
This is a BEAUTIFUL little kitchen. It has so many cool things that make me want to go back in time so I can play with it as a kid... but that's why I have a daughter! Now I have a great excuse to play with it :-)
We bought her this KidKraft kitchen, a set of pots and pans and fake food and she LOVES IT! As soon as we go downstairs in the morning, that's the first place where she will go to play so my husband and I are thrilled about buying her this.
The one big issue that I have is the instruction manual... I don't know about the guy who said it took him a little bit over 2 hours to build this because my husband and I did it TOGETHER and it took us around 4 - and we are both engineers. There are quite a few issues with the instructions that drive me crazy AND with the screws that come along with this set.
To give you a concrete example:
All the screws come separated and labeled for you A - Q I think. However, there are two types of A screws, two types of G, etc... WHY? Oh... well I didn't even realize that this was happening until we noticed that some of the A screws have a white topping and the others don't. Ok, that makes sense because the white ones should go in every external facing surface of the kitchen so it looks prettier. Why don't you TELL me in the instructions, to make sure I pick the white topping screws? Why don't they name those screws something else? Or why don't they make ALL the screws have a white topping?
I do not regret buying this at all but I do recommend that you look VERY CLOSELY at the instructions, sometimes even encourage you to jump ahead a few steps so you understand what they want you to do, and also pay attention to the top of the screw so you use the right ones.

title: Good toddler kitchen
text: Product arrived very well packaged, with each piece cushioned and labeled.  Especially nice that the bolts, screws, etc were individually shrink wrapped and labeled on a piece of cardboard, making them easy to account for.  Even so, the unit did take a couple of hours to assemble.  Seems to be very sturdy and durable, only problem was the door catches, which were so stiff the entire unit tipped forward when trying to pry open the doors.  We resolved this by removing the catches, and the doors seem to stay closed fine without them.  My almost 2-1/2 year old granddaughter is having a great time organizing and reorganizing her wooden food on the many shelves, cooking on the burners, and washing in the sink.  The kitchen is a perfect size for her now, so she will probably outgrow it by the time she is 4 or so.  All in all, a great toy - I do have to chuckle over the concept of a kitchen labeled "Vintage" that includes a microwave and refrigerator door water/ice dispenser...

title: Adorable, Sturdy, but instructions stink - Mind your "R"s and "Q"s
text:
After 2.5hrs of 4 very capable and sober adults breaking up into teams to put this together....It turned out looking adorable. But the route to get there was annoying as hell. One reason it took so long was on our fruitless search for the "Q" labeled screws. The instructions called for them, but they were no where to be found. We looked and looked, and tore through every scrap of the box, and ultimately we went to our toolbench and found similar screws and applied washers, and it made a good replacement. That took one of the two teams on a 45 minute diversion. However, when it was finally assembled we strangely had two "R" screws leftover! You guessed it, the instructions are so poorly written an edited that what the book call Q screws, the nut/bolt package called R screws. See the picture I uploaded.

Then there were the consistent diagrams that weren't to scale, or that left out images of holes/edges which are needed by the assembler to figure out which end is up when inserting screws.

Lastly, it was the "more is better" concept of screws. There were dozens of different shapes and sizes of screws, and hundreds of pieces. If you've ever assembled IKEA, well this made IKEA look simple, and honestly IKEA is simple compared to this. IKEA has figured out a way to use 1 assembling piece for every 4 or 6 that this package contained.

At 2:30am on Dec 23rd however, it looked adorable by the time we were finished, but it warned me off this brand of kids products to buy in the future. There is just no forethought put into the assembly process or instructions itself, and I'd rather reward a company who puts more effort in this area. The finished picture includes an extra foam-core backsplash that I attached with some multi-heart colored contact paper. Hopefully some of the toys won't fall behind and get stuck with a backsplash added. Neither the accessories nor the foam-core backsplash come with this kitchen; you are just purchasing the white kitchen

title: Well Priced, Well Built, Fun!
text:
This kitchen is certainly good looking, and the MDF gives it a much more refined finish over the similarly priced plastic options. The doors and hinges all function very nicely, and after 3 months of play, I can't find anything that looks worn or prone to getting broken. The phone may disappear since it isn't corded to the set, but that would be my child's fault and not the designers. After using this, I don't know why anyone would go with the plastic options given the price.

I don't really have any negatives about the set, but I do think there are some drawbacks that some people may need to be aware of before purchasing. In true IKEA-style fashion, it is "flat packed", and next to nothing is preassembled. You will be responsible for attaching every handle, every hinge, every door. I wouldn't say any step is difficult, but it is time consuming. Also, there are three dials that click for the oven and range, but beyond that it is all imagination. No batteries, no electronics, no buttons to push. It is entirely self directed play, and your child will have to use his imagination. We actually bought a cheap little kitchen timer to put with the set. It really just depends on what you or your child prefer as to the level of interactivity.
