title: Cute kitchen, beware of parts problems.
text:
Very cute kitchen, nicely sized for my toddler. He likes all the cubbies to store and play with his cookware and food (purchased separately). That said, I agree with the reviews which said it's sometimes confusing which screws to use. You have to keep track yourself of inside versus outside as instructions don't tell you. Several of the boards were mislabeled and one was completely incorrect. Once assembled, there were 3 issues. The bottom screw into the bar holding up the microwave station would not tighten all the way, leaving it a little wiggly. The top piece for the fridge was the wrong part (received two #8 and no 5). The side piece of the microwave was too long in back. I contacted customer service via email about the boards. After numerous back and forth emails, they are sending me a replacement for the top of the fridge. Regarding the microwave side, they said that was just how it was manufactured, nothing can be done. She said they have this kitchen in office, and theirs is like that too. You would think that if they're aware of the issue, they would make replacement parts in the correct size. Dissatisfied that they could not offer a solution.

Update: I received the replacement part #5. Unfortunately, it is cut improperly just like part 38, making it too long. I've contacted customer service again but doubt they will have a solution.

I have found after some use, the faucet has come loose and looks like it'll break off in the near future. I feel this is great way to stimulate your child's imagination and we've actually started storing my daughter's snacks in the cabinets so we can get an idea when she's getting hungry. One of our main concerns is this can tip over if standing on its own. To prevent any injuries, I've moved it against the wall and will fastened it with a wall anchor or screws. Those things were always getting lost. The doors have slammed my kids fingers in them more times than I can count. The kitchen has tipped over multiple times onto my children. My kids are not rough on things so this kitchen should of lasted longer in my opinion. I am now in the process of looking for a new toy kitchen for my now 5 and 2 year olds. title: The directions and assembly sucks. Fire everyone involved in designing them.
text:
I'm currently awake at 1:30AM on Christmas Eve. The reason, of course, is because of this KidKraft Vintage Kitchen set. Don't listen to what anyone has to say about the "easy assembly." The product arrives, essentially, in a pile of loose parts. Look at that picture again - think it looks cute? Well, now imagine yourself putting together every little plastic piece, snapping together every wooden board, and attaching every screw. They literally assembled nothing at the factory, aside from perhaps the plastic window on the oven door and the hinge on the microwave. The toy has 35 (!!!) steps, and the manual is essentially inscrutable - on occasion, the person who wrote the directions made some useful drawing to clarify, but for the most part, you have to sit there for twenty minutes figuring out which direction to put the hinge or attempting to understand why a plastic piece has multiple holes when it only requires two screws (I've now put it together, seemingly correctly, and I still don't understand that bit of genius).

Bottom line: it is indeed cute, and I'm sure my son will love it. But the assembly/directions are a mess. Save yourself a couple hours to put it together.

title: I pity da fool who waits till Xmas Eve!
text:
It's a great little set: very well-designed and constructed. It just takes hours to put together. As others have noted, it's not that the assembly is confusing or especially difficult - it just has dozens of parts and a complete alphabet of hardware pieces.

Some advice:
1. use a blade to slice open each hardware section; keep the pieces in each section until you need them
2. do NOT use a power screwdriver, never mind a drill. Everything is pre-drilled and fitted, so you'll go deeper than necessary
3. be especially ginger when turning screws into plastic parts - these are the only ones that are poorly designed and made, and it's easy to snap off a plastic backing if you try to get even hand tight
4. there's a light dust over all the pieces from manufacturing, so be ready with a damp paper towel to finish the job

once assembled it's a cool little set that our daughter loves for all it's details

text: My 1 1/2 yr old plays with this kitchen constantly.  It is a great size and the doors are easy for him to open and close without frustrating him.  Putting it together was definitely an undertaking.  I did it by myself and it took about 5 1/2 hours.  I probably could have done it faster but I wanted to make sure I didn't screw it up and took my time.  The instructions were easy to follow, the hardest part was figuring out exactly how the hinges should attach and not putting them on backwards.  Some of the other reviews gave hints that I thought were helpful, especially screwing in your screws to the plastic parts before you actually attach the piece.  They are not threaded and I think doing this really made things easier when you are in strange positions.  One big hiccup was at the very end, the hole for the sink was not big enough and did not fit.  I had to actually get help with this and we had to chisel out a small part to make it fit.  And even by doing that we still had to really hammer it in.  I would suggest first thing before you put anything together make sure the sink fits into the designated hole.  There was no way I was taking it all apart at that point to return it!  Despite this major problem we still love the kitchen enough to not even subtract from the rating.

title: Doesn't look as nice as pictures.
text:
After agonizing over which play kitchen to buy for my 1.5 year old I picked this one due to good reviews and the clean white look. I didn't want plastic and I thought this was all painted or coated wood and MDF but that's not true so it doesn't look as nice as I'd hoped. The front doors are all solid feeling and painted or coated cheap wood or particle board and looks decent except for a few dings it came with but the rest is MDF covered in laminate and it doesn't look very nice with the white because the seam around the edge shows. It's a fine line but it's a dark line so the part I'm looking down at is very cheapy looking unfortunately. I honestly wish I would've shelled out some more cash and gotten something nicer. The white one I got also cane with some light blue marks on the counter top part that won't wash off. But once you unpack even half the peices there's no way they are going back in the box so make sure you really want it before you start building.

Other observations:

It had a noticeable new furniture/chemical smell while building and after a few months continues to smell that way inside the cabinets as they don't air out as much.

Make sure you have a drill just in case. At least with a screwdriver bit. Goes much faster. There are a million and one screws!

Make sure you put the painted white screws on any bit that is facing out. They don't differentiate in the instructions and it's a pain to go back and change them.

You get what you pay for. Honestly I'm not sure why or how this kitchen is compaired with the pottery barn one. Pottery Barn's version is almost twice the price but it's twice the nice in my opinion. The doors sound more solid and the whole thing just looks nicer. The children's musium near my house has a few peices of the pottery barn kitchen sets and it's holding up great even with constant public use. The kid kraft one seems like it would break within a week or two of such use.

The plastics on the kid kraft kitchen are very cheap. A few months in nothing has broken, yay! I just hope it keeps going that way. Either way they are not super nice to look at.

In conclusion I wish I would've bought something nicer that sits flush with the wall and didn't have those weird bits sticking out the back.

title: WOW!  I LOVE THIS KITCHEN!
text: This is the second kitchen I have purchased.  One in white and one in turquoise.  I must admit i was a little overwhelmed when the flat box arrived and i realized how much assembly was required.... But the assembly was relatively easy, although it did take hours to complete.  I followed it step by step.  I learned a few things after putting the first kitchen together a year before i bought the second one.  Assembly on a table makes it go much easier.  I took all the pieces out and stacked them by number (each piece is clearly marked).  The only confusing part is that there are two sets of some screws with the same letter (A & E)  just make sure when you are using these that you save the ones which have been painted (on the head) for the outside of the kitchen pieces.  Silver goes on the inside.  All outside panels should have colored head screws.  The same with doors.  I would buy this kitchen again and again.  The kids love it!

There were a couple of time consuming steps (such as screwing the legs on) but otherwise everything went just fine. I put it together alone, no help from my husband or anyone else in about 2 hours. Best of all, my daughter is going to absolutely love it. A great price for such a nice product.

title: Great for 2 yr old, but not the sturdiest of options
text: We bought this for our daughter for her 2nd birthday. She was thrilled. She had enjoyed every play kitchen she came across so we thought she'd like one at home. It took a really LONG for my husband to assemble (at least 3 hrs?). All the parts were present, but it was tedious (you've been warned). The size is on the small side. It fits my standard 2 year old just fine, but it was pretty small for a 3.5 yr old that came over to play. It didn't stop them from playing with it, but just something to keep in mind. The sink just sits in the hole designated as such, and just glue or screw in. My biggest complaint is when I went to move it across the room with barely any toys in it, I gripped under the microwave and a screw stripped through the wood, so not the sturdiest of play kitchens. Then again, I wasn't willing to pay $400+ for a Pottery Barn version etc.

title: It's really difficult and it take ALL DAY to put together
text: It's very cute once you are done assembling it. However, IT TAKES ALL FREAKING DAY. The directions dont have words so GOOD LUCK. Don't have long acrylic nails because it makes it 50x harder to put in any lock nuts as they are Itty bitty. Tip: hold the wrench on the nut and use a screw driver to screw it all the way in. Screw count was off. Genuinely buy it if you like assembling time consuming things. My 18 month old loves it so that's all that matters.

title: My granddaughter loved it but . . . . . . . .
text: I really like it but it was a pain to put together.  It took two of us 4 hours to assemble on Christmas Eve.  All but two of the boards were marked, as was the hardware, but the hardware was sometimes split between two areas, making you question whether you had enough of a certain piece.  The instructions were all visual, which were ok, but could be confusing.  I was disappointed that by the time we put the last two boards on, they were not flush with the rest of the kitchen.  They are in the back,but still, with the quality of what we were working with I would have expected everything to match up.  Also we could not attach the phone because one of the holes for the hardware was missing.

The best part was when our daughter woke up and saw it, her jaw dropped and she immediately started playing with it. She's only stopped playing with it to sleep. It was worth all the hard work.

We had originally intended on buying the pottery barn retro kitchen because I like the white and chrome. The last thing I want is some pink or primary colored kitchen in the middle of my home. With shipping the Pottery Barn one was going to run close to a thousand dollars. This kitchen is nearly as cute at a fraction of the cost.

I would definitely recommend this product.

title: High Quality, Worth the Effort
text:
Received today and put together today. A bit daunting when you open the box, but instructions were easy to follow. Took about 2 hours to put together but not because it is hard, because there are a lot of pieces. The door hinges are the most annoying part because of the wrench work. For anyone looking for tips on putting it together, I recommend putting on the stool legs on the bottom board before putting on the side walls so the wrench work goes faster. I had also read a comment about the white screws before I put it together so I made sure to look ahead to the final version so I made sure that the white screws always faced out.

The quality is really good and I really couldn't believe how great everything lined up.

Will update the review after my daughter gets it, but so far seems a perfect size and isn't a cheap looking, awful colored plastic kitchen that I want to hide from sight!

title: We love our KidKraft Kitchen
text:
We love our KidKraft Kitchen.

PROS:
- Perfect height for our one year hold
- Comes with all the appliances of a real kitchen
- Decent quality - but a few flaws
- Sink handles turn like you're turning to water "on" and "off"
- Stove burners click when you turn them to resemble and actual stove
- Refrigerator door comes with a spot for water and our New Sprouts by Learning Resources cups fit perfectly

CONS
- Decent quality, but after a few days of use the paint has chipped in a few places
- A few of the doors don't line up perfectly, causing a door to squeak

WISHES
- I wish the stove opened like an actual stove
- For long term use, the kitchen could be taller, but that's if your kids will play with it beyond age 3 1/2 - 4

Overall, the quality is mainly what you get for the price tag and it perfect for LOs. We also like this kitchen because it fits in with our living room and doesn't stand out like some other kitchens.

text: I'm writing this review more than 4 months after ordering and receiving the KidKraft Vintage Kitchen.  My wife and I purchased this as a Christmas gift for our granddaughter and it has been one of her favorite playthings consistently since she received it.  The quality of the materials/construction is excellent - standing up extremely well to sometimes rugged play.  And in addition to all this, I need to give special kudos to KidKraft for their customer service.  We discovered several months after purchasing this that one part (a decorative "grille") had been missing from the original package - our daughter informed us of this.  Even though it was technically beyond the 90 day warrantee period, I contacted KidKraft and asked if they could send the missing piece.  Without a hitch, they immediately agreed to do so and sent the missing part at no cost to us, and it arrived three days later.  That is the kind of customer service that will build a loyal customer base!  I can't recommend these folks highly enough!!

title: PRODUCT NOT AS ADVERTISED
text: Clearly, there are several versions of this kitchen being sold.  My kitchen is smaller than the advertised measurements, but most noticeably, it does NOT have a spinning plate in the microwave.  The bottom of the microwave is just a flat white board.  Also, the faucet is almost touching the bottom of the microwave so there would be no room for the knob that you spin.  I did a ton of research before purchasing this kitchen, and the spinning microwave plate was one of the main reasons I bought the kitchen.  I called Amazon to see if I could get a replacement microwave, but that piece is not available.  Also, the kitchen took well over 5 hours to assemble.  Given the number of pieces, there's no possible way to do it faster. I've read some reviews that suggested the door hinges were already attached.  Ours were not attached, so those customers must have received a different version of the kitchen.  Amazon offered to send me a new kitchen if I disassembled my kitchen and sent it back, but they could not say for sure that I would have the correct microwave in the new kitchen.  So all I received was a $20 credit off of my NEXT Amazon purchase.  Overall, I'm extremely disappointed with this purchase.  I should have bought the Teamson kitchen.

title: Missing part with no way to replace
text:
After unpacking everything and assembling most of it I discovered that they included two of one piece, and it was missing the oven door piece. I went to the website to report a missing piece only to find out it is out of stock and there's no way to get it. So that's great.

Also, the instructions could be a lot more clear. Some of the screws have versions with white heads and also some with silver heads, but they're labeled the same as the instructions and packaged in completely different spots. So you see in the instructions to use the "A" screws, so you find the "A" screws and use them. Then a few steps later you see another step to use "A" screws but there aren't enough, only to realize you opened and used the white "A" screws when you should have used the silver "A" screws that were packaged separately, so now you have to unscrew them and replace them. Just label them differently if they are different, it's not that hard.

title: A "Real" Kitchen That's Easy On the Eyes
text:
We bought this kitchen for our 1 1/2-year-old son after having already bought wooden Melissa and Doug Fridge Food ([[ASIN:B00146G71U Melissa & Doug Fridge Food Set]], Pantry Food [[ASIN:B00146LV5C Melissa & Doug Wooden Pantry Products]], and Cutting Food [[ASIN:B000GKD09C Melissa & Doug Cutting Food Box]]. We had also already bought a realistic-looking pots and pans set ([...]) and cooking utencils set ([...]) from IKEA. We felt the toys needed context. Anyway, we chose the KidKraft Vintage Kitchen in white because:
1) It looked the most real-looking, which is what I preferred as a child.
2) It wasn't something we'd mind having and looking at in our own kitchen, which is where we had decided to put it.
3) It came with a fridge, which many play kitchens do not. He needed somewhere to put all that perishable food!
4) It provided enough storage space for all of his play food and dishes.
5) We're familiar with and confident in the quality of KidKraft, knowing that this kitchen would stand up to many years of use.
Though our son still hasn't gotten into pretend play yet, he does enjoy standing at the kitchen and playing by opening and closing the cabinets (which were a little tight at first), picking up the phone, turning the clicking knobs on the stove, fiddling with the faucet, and pulling things out of the fridge and pantry to inspect. We're very happy with this purchase and would highly recommend it!

title: Pay Attention to Details
text:
Don't let the negative reviews on this kitchen turn you off. It's really not that hard to put together. It only took me 2 1/2 hours to do it, and that's with making the mistake of putting it together with my two year old running around trying to help.

Yes, there are some screws and seemingly awkward things to do to build the kitchen, but it's worth it. It is totally cute and practical- I purchased the white vintage kitchen for my little guy, and he loves cooking while I work in the kitchen. Keep this in mind while you put it together.

Now, brace yourself. The directions are clear, but they are only pictorial directions. There are no written directions. Because of this, you need to look really closely at the directions and pay attention to which side of the board/kitchen is facing up in the picture. Most of the hinges come attached. Only one set is not, so that's helpful. Also, the screws and bolts come in a labeled cardboard bubble strip. For the love of all things, DON'T open them up until you take note of which screw is labeled with whatever letter. If you are liable to forget, get some sandwich bags and label them with a black marker and put the corresponding screw in the proper bag. You will thank yourself later.

As to the actual putting together, I agree that it would be tons easier if the plastic pieces were threaded. However, it's just one extra step for you. DON'T try to attach the plastic pieces directly to the kitchen without first pre-screwing the screws into the legs or plastic door latch. You will be cursing within one minute if you don't take this step. Just twist the screw all the way in and remove it before you go on to the step of actually attaching it to the structure. On a side note, don't use a drill. Stick with a regular screw driver. If you use a drill with particle board, you are liable to accidentally torque the screw and over tighten it, which will cause the particle board to crack and leave you with a door that may just fall off the hinge because the board is compromised.

These are my words of advice. Hope they helped. Oh, if you do run in to any trouble, don't hesitate to call the KidKraft help number that comes with the directions.

title: Nice finished product with a few quality control/construction issues
text:
The finished product looks great but it was a pain to put together. I had a couple specific issues:

- One of the holes for the burners was marked but not pre-drilled. I'm sure this was a one-off defect as everything else was pre-drilled perfectly. I can drill a hole but wasn't expecting to use power tools for this project.
- There are some 'tools' included but you should expect to use your own basic tools like a ratcheting screwdriver to put this together.
- It isn't totally clear from the instructions but there are screws that are painted white that belong on the outside of the structure. Putting this together piece by piece, it's really hard to tell when to use which color screw. Personally I would pay rather pay the extra couple cents per piece to have all white hardware.
- On the back there are a couple pieces which hang out about a half an inch longer than all the others. This is clearly a defect as everything else lines up perfectly and I know I followed all instructions carefully. Will my kid care? No. But disappointing for me after spending several hours putting this thing together. I may saw them off to make the back flush but I don't know if it's worth it. If trying to back up flush against a wall this might be a problem.

At the end of the day everything important for functionality (door hinges, etc.) lines up together perfectly and the kitchen seems very sturdy so I still give it 4 stars for the price. I knew what I was getting into anyways after reading reviews.

title: We have no ikea furniture and I had really no experience putting anything like this together

I did not have to drill extra holes at all. Although the directions where only pictures, it's fairly straightforward. We have no ikea furniture and I had really no experience putting anything like this together, but I had no trouble. It looks cute and is very sturdy. Before I started putting it together, I did make sure that all the prices where present and that nothing was chipped or scratched. I recommend you do the same.

title: Perfect Play Kitchen
text: I bought this for my 2-year-old's Christmas present this year. I got it a few hours ago and assembled it while also working around my very interested son. The instructions we sort of your standard unassembled furniture type of instruction so it's not too bad if you're used to that kind of stuff. All the wood and particle board pieces were labeled with numbered stickers and all the little screws and what-not were in a single package separated and labeled appropriately. The slightly more difficult part was that the plastic parts (the knobs, sink, etc.) did not have labels so you have to go off looks which for the most part isn't too bad but there are a couple pieces that look pretty similar so I made a wild guess when it came to that initially and lucked out but that would've been slightly annoying to go back and fix further on. I also appreciate that all the screw are of a good quality so you won't easily strip the screws like the ones a lot of other companies provided to save a few cents. I also noted that the wood wasn't easily messed up either like if my screwdriver slipped, there would be no scratch on the paint as immediate evidence. They have a couple screws labeled the same but they just vary by one type having a white head so if it's going to be visible, you'll want to grab those to use but others are hidden so you could just grab the regular silver ones. I didn't time how long it took me to assemble but at least a couple hours while working around a curious toddler. Everything feels pretty study and my son is already all about it. Another thing too was that when I was attaching the little KidKraft emblem on the freezer door, one of the pieces that I was supposed to screw on broke off but I was at least able to make do with using hot glue to get things in order there. I doubt you'd even know unless I told you because, like I said, it's sturdy. It's just my son's size (he's about 35" tall), looks great, and should last for years!

title: Love this Kitchen!

They really aren't necessary and my daughter had a really hard time opening the cabinet doors.  It was similar to child proofing your own kitchen.  I removed these pieces and it's more practical now.  I would definitely recommend this product.

title: Assembly time.
text:
Are you a new father slighty overwhelmed by a sprawling professional career as well as family commitments during the holiday season? If so do not purchase this product as it will rape what little Christmas spirit you have left due to the 4 hour assembly time. I started optimistic, as I am about a 6.5 out of ten on the handy scale; however this product makes assembly almost impossible without a masters in cheap furniture assembly. It make an Ikea real size kitchen seem like a menial task.

As I laid out the dozens, on dozens of parts I new that it was going to be an adventure, literally, not one single hinge is assembled and there are possible over a hundred pieces of fastening hardware at a minimum. I hope, that on Christmas day when Santa drops this thing off for my daughter that she has never loved something so much because it left me not so excited about the birth of our savior, but needing a trip to the chirporator for the multiple hours spent leaning over this toy.

Kid Craft- I beg of you, as my wife will not listen to my suggestions on almost anything - to please post some type of warning like "multiple drill batteries required, ensure that you charge them over night so that you dont have to stop"

In the middle of assembly, as I was running out of water and worried that I may perish in my basement next to the litter box my wife brought me breakfast. The subsistence was necessary due, I haven't felt that mal nourished since Iraq in '09. Following the meal of suasage and over medium eggs I dove back in, only to find that I installed multiple hinged incorrectly due to the pour directions that are given to you.

If you do purchase this - Stay Golden. My heart will be with you.

title: Nice find!
text: Surprisingly high quality for $80.  All the pre-drilled holes are in the right places, such that it's solid and doesn't wobble, and all the doors line up with 1/8" tolerance.  However, assembly isn't trivial as did take me 3 hours to assemble, and some of the instructions pictures could have been larger, and they could have designated where to use painted screw heads vs. non-painted screw heads, but made some guesses and it all worked out.  One improvement suggestion is to use less secure door latches, or nethaps break off one tab. My 3 year old had difficulty opening and closing the doors without slamming, so I had to take them off.  As long as the floor is level, doors will stay closed.  I paired it with the JOYIN 135 piece play food and Cute Stone Kids pot/pan set which was the perfect size and all plastic to be drop-able (less dings in my hardwood floor).  Disassemb-able food in the Cute Stone set is very unique.  But beware that the JOYIN set is like ping-pong ball plastic so will bounce a bit on hardwood floors, mainly only a problem with the oranges are they are almost completely round so roll off, but everything else will settle. Recommend washing with dish soap, as they seemed oily out of the packaging.  Didn't want that in mouths.

title: Stay away from this product! Buyer beware.
text:
I‚Äôm not one for writing reviews, but I had to get this out there. Purchasing this for my child was the worst experience. I gave it one star because the review required it. Otherwise, I wouldn‚Äôt give it that much.
To start, the item comes disassembled. Which normally is not an issue for me. This item came in 500 pcs. Obviously that‚Äôs an exaggeration, but no exaggeration, this item took me almost 4 hours to put together with all the pieces and directions that were hard to read and understand.
This was the real reason I had to write this review. If you notice in the pictures attached, you will see that a major piece that holds the item together was manufactured incorrectly. Meaning the oven door could not be attached unless I cut new insets for the hinges of the door. The most aggravating is, that door is the last to be put on. What a waste of time and money. Please don‚Äôt waste your time with this.

title: Feet unbearable!
text: Echoing some of the previous reviews, this is much to short for a toddler. Most of the kitchen went together okay (even though they are just pictures), but the legs were horrible. I used a drill with an allen wrench attachment because hand tightening was impossible. It got most of the way in then stripped the screw head. We called and they sent a replacement saying "soak the screws in dish soap" (not kidding). We coated the screws and used the drill again, and it worked for the one foot that was now pre-threaded (thanks to the first and only stripped screw), but the others got various ways in before stripping. I was able to move up an allen wrench size and twist the legs on (rather than using the wrench), but even that only went so far. We had to Gorilla Glue the 2 loosest feet on! Not impressed. (And yes, the feet are critical to give the bottom doors clearance so they can open without scraping the floor. In retrospect, we should have gotten a white block the size of the bottom of the kitchen board, and screwed it in through the holes drilled for the feet. At least this way we could adjust the height of the kitchen, too.

text:

title: Cute little kitchen but HORRIBLE to assemble
text:
This kitchen makes ikea product assembly desirable. It is probably the worst I have ever come across. The instructions are terrible and unclear (it doesn't show you which side/end of each panel you are screwing into so by the time you get to putting all the pieces together half of them have hinges facing the wrong way or upside down.). There are over 30 steps and about 15 different screw sizes and types, not to mention different washers and such. It's just terrible and I'm someone who actually usually like putting things together and am normally quite good at it.

Due to the nature of our set up this year I had to wait until Christmas Eve after the kids went to bed to put this together because we had no where to store the finished product where the kids wouldn't see it. So, I was up until 3AM and still didn't finish. We explained that Santa's elves were feeling a little behind so did most of the work and asked us to help with finishing touches. Which I then spent another 2 hours doing on Christmas morning.

Do yourselves a favor and just gt another damn kitchen. The Ikea one is a dream to put together and looks super cute and is the same price.

It gets 3 stars because the kids really like it and it blends into the background nicely as an added piece of furniture.

title: adorable and gender-neutral design
text:
Pros: adorable and gender-neutral design, durable construction, lots of little details like stove knobs that click, and very reasonably priced.

Cons: assembly

We bought this kitchen for my daughter for Christmas, so it's been in use at our house for six months now. I really wanted to buy her a Pottery Barn kitchen, but didn't want to spend $500+ on it, so I settled on this as an alternative.

Pros first: it's really cute. I didn't want a lurid pink kitchen, or one of the plastic ones. This kitchen is made of laminated mdf - so while it's not exactly solid wood construction, it's certainly nicer than the typical pink plastic kitchens you see. Assembled, it looks just like the picture.

It seems really solidly built. It doesn't wobble, and it's held up to 6 months of fairly constant use extremely well. I was originally a bit worried about the moving pieces like the faucet (which swivels) and the faucet handles, but they've held up quite well to toddler abuse.

This kitchen has a lot of little details like stove knobs that make clicking noises, and doors that click shut. My daughter particularly enjoys the pretend fridge water dispenser.

Comparatively speaking, the Pottery Barn kitchen is undoubtedly of higher quality and looks nicer, but for hundreds of dollars less, this is a really cute, solidly constructed kitchen that should last the average kid many years.

There is only really one con: assembly. I expected to have to assemble it, but seriously, you have to assemble every single little piece. Nothing comes pre-assembled. You have to put the hinges and hardware and any stickers on every door, you have to put the water dispenser on the fridge door, you have to screw in all the little clips that hold all the doors closed. It took my husband and me probably a combined 4 hours to assemble it, and my husband works in a cabinet shop. No joke. The instructions are not clear or straightforward and there are so many tiny pieces and parts. It's worth the effort, but be prepared to spend hours putting this thing together.

Overall, we're really happy with it, and are glad we didn't despair at the assembly process and just send it back.
